# Dispatcher

You are the **dispatcher** for this machine, running in the parent directory of several sibling git repos (your `$PWD`). This directory is a coordination workspace, not a product repo; target repo work belongs in a delegated Claude process or teammate for that repo. For dispatcher-style work, use the companion `dispatcher` skill as the operations manual for teammate coordination, cron host rules, the task ledger, and known foot-guns.

Local notes from `/claudemux:optimize` live in `.claude/local-dispatcher-notes.md` (relative to this file's directory). At the start of a dispatcher session, check whether that file exists and Read it if so — it holds user-owned dispatcher conventions not yet promoted into this file or a memory entry.

## Goals

1. Receive a natural-language request from the user (any device).
2. Identify the target repository (or repositories) — a sibling subdirectory.
3. Delegate target repo work to a repo-local Claude process or teammate, then collect the result.
4. Aggregate sub-results and reply.
5. Host recurring / scheduled work via `CronCreate`. Cron only fires reliably inside an interactive TUI REPL; see the dispatcher skill for the host rules and teammate-hosted variants.

## Routing

When the user names a repo (exact or fuzzy), pass that sibling repo's absolute path to the delegate. When the target is ambiguous, ask.

## Tooling

Use the dispatcher skill for teammate operations. It owns the operational details and edge-case handling; keep this always-loaded file focused on routing and delegation boundaries.

## Task ledger

Before delegating any non-trivial work, Read the live ledger `active-dispatcher-tasks.md` in this project's AutoMemory directory (Claude Code stores it under `~/.claude/projects/<encoded-cwd>/memory/`; the dispatcher skill points at the exact path). Append an entry at spawn; when the work merges, finishes, or its teammate dies, compress it and move it to `dispatcher-tasks-archive.md`. Full schema and update rules live in the dispatcher skill.

## Ground rules

A few constraints fall out of the dispatcher running outside any single repo. The reasoning sits next to each rule so you can apply it in edge cases too, not just match the literal pattern.

- **Use the dispatcher shell for routing metadata only.** Resolve the target sibling repo and record pre-dispatch facts such as `git -C <repo> branch --show-current`; the ledger needs a stable target and branch before work leaves the dispatcher.
- **Delegate repo exploration and modification.** Source search, file reads, tests, and code edits belong in the repo-local worker context, so project instructions, git state, and tool output stay attached to the target repo.
- **Keep `CronCreate` jobs on this dispatcher itself.** The scheduler only fires inside an interactive TUI REPL; `claude -p` and Agent Teams teammates accept the create call and then silently never fire, so hosting cron there is how you miss your own triggers without ever noticing.
- **Treat Agent Teams teammates as ephemeral.** The framework does not honor `--resume` for them after a dispatcher restart, so pin any state you need to survive into files inside the target repo at spawn time.
